<h2>Form</h2>
<p>
    The <strong>form-level state machine and lifecycle actions</strong>, sitting <em>above</em> the field-level
    <a href="/intents/validation/">Validation Intent</a> and the Web Validation project (which own per-field rules and
    validity). Web Validation answers &ldquo;is this field valid?&rdquo;; the Form block answers
    <strong>&ldquo;what is the state of the whole form, and how do I reset / submit / initialize it?&rdquo;</strong>
</p>
<p>
    It is a <strong>candidate (draft) composition manifest</strong> — like <a href="/blocks/droplist/">Droplist</a>, it
    composes existing intents rather than re-specifying their behavior, and adds only the aggregate state and lifecycle
    actions the native platform doesn't expose. No implementation ships yet; this documents the contract for review.
</p>

<h3>The contract</h3>
<p>Grounded in the native <code>&lt;form&gt;</code> element and the Constraint Validation API:</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>State</strong> — aggregate <code>valid</code>/<code>invalid</code>, <code>touched</code>/<code>untouched</code>,
        <code>focused</code>/<code>unfocused</code>, <code>dirty</code>/<code>pristine</code> across fields.</li>
    <li><strong>Values</strong> — <code>initialValues</code> (seed) / <code>defaultValues</code> (reset target) / current
        <code>values</code>, kept distinct; the dirty check is current-vs-initial.</li>
    <li><strong>Actions</strong> — <code>submit</code>, <code>reset</code> (to defaults), <code>clear</code> (to empty),
        <code>initialize(initialValues?)</code> (re-seed and mark pristine — the new baseline).</li>
</ul>

<h3>Native-first grounding</h3>
<p>
    The block augments a real <code>&lt;form&gt;</code>, it never replaces it. <code>FormData</code> reads current values;
    the Constraint Validation API supplies per-field validity; and <code>formAssociated</code> custom elements participate
    via <code>ElementInternals</code> form-lifecycle callbacks (<code>formResetCallback</code>,
    <code>formStateRestoreCallback</code>). The Form block adds only the aggregate state and actions the platform leaves to
    userland — it does not re-implement field validity or submission the browser already performs.
</p>

<h3>Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/HTMLFormElement">HTMLFormElement</a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>The block binds to a real <code>&lt;form&gt;</code> — its <code>reset()</code>/<code>submit()</code> and the
            <code>submit</code>/<code>reset</code>/<code>formdata</code> events are the substrate the actions wrap.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData">FormData</a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>Reads current <code>values</code> from the live form — no parallel value store to drift.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Constraint_validation">Constraint Validation API</a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>Per-field <code>validity</code> comes from the platform; the block only <em>aggregates</em> it to form level.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/ElementInternals">ElementInternals / formAssociated</a></td>
        <td>Baseline 2026</td>
        <td>Custom fields join the native form and respond to reset/restore via the form-lifecycle callbacks.</td>
    </tr>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h3>Composition (defers to owning intents)</h3>
<we-data-table>
<table class="data-table">
    <tr><th>Concern</th><th>Owning intent</th><th>How Form composes it</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Field → form validity merge</td>
        <td><a href="/intents/validation/">Validation</a></td>
        <td>Form validity merges from field validity through the swappable <code>ValidityMergeRegistry</code> (#212 / #004
            OP-1); the Form block consumes the <code>MergedValidity</code> hand-off shape and does <strong>not</strong> bake
            the merge math — closing the &ldquo;last-writer vs. strictest&rdquo; question by deferring to the ratified
            strategy plane (native-first default: source-reduction over named sources).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Unsaved-changes guard</td>
        <td><a href="/intents/exit-guard/">Exit Guard</a></td>
        <td>Arms the navigation guard (#129) from <code>dirty</code> so leaving a modified, unsubmitted form prompts.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>Submit lifecycle</td>
        <td><a href="/intents/feedback/">Feedback</a> / <a href="/intents/reliability/">Reliability</a></td>
        <td>In-flight / success / error of a submit are surfaced through the Feedback and Reliability intents, not a
            bespoke form-only mechanism.</td>
    </tr>
</table>
</we-data-table>

<h3>Provenance</h3>
<p>
    Surfaced as a gap — no block answers the whole-form state/lifecycle question, only field-level validity. Built fresh on
    the native form + validation primitives. (The legacy <code>plateau</code> repo is explicitly <strong>not</strong> a model
    and was not consulted.)
</p>
